div.p:
Next vnto our thoughts, the Lord will examine our wordes, yea all our words, Non tam malitiosa, quam otiosa, aswel such as are spoken in our myrth, as in our malice, for of euery idle word saith Christ, that men shal speake, they shall giue an account thereof at the day of iudgement.
Matt. 12.36. And surely all are idle that are not profitable, and tend either to the glorie of God, or good of his Church;
Hierom: super Leuit. 12. Quicquid non adificat audiētes in periculum vertitur eloquentium, whatsoeuer doth not edifie the hearer, turnes to the danger of the speaker.

Now if such be the conscience that shall accuse vs: then blessed is the good conscience that shall quit vs, in that great day, of which the Apostle speaketh, when he saith;
2. Cor. 1.12.
               Our reioycing is the testimonie of our conscience, that in simplicitie and godly purenes, and not in fleshly wisedome, but by the grace of God, we haue had our conuersation in this world, and most of all to you wards.

Lastly. Be it they yet say, Good God if it must needs be so, let vs be ruled with some pittifull prince, and haue some societie that good is: but he shal answere;

euen with the diuell, and his angels, Pro domino habebitis diabolum maiorem, pro socijs vero doemones minores, Ye shall haue the prince of diuels for your king, and lesser diuels for your companions:

                  Reuel. 9.6. ye shall seeke death & shall not finde it, and shall desire to die, & death shall flie from you.
